Title: Linking forum posts - advchem-001-01-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Mistake in 7.2 Problem Examples Video: That 100 is wrong!
Input.posts:
In the 7.2 Problem Examples Video , there is a conceptual mistake at 2:13, when the lecturer introduces 100 as the 100% of the concentration (the initial concentration). However, what that assumption is actually telling us is that the initial concentration was 100 M!, which contradicts the given equation, which says that 1/[A]$$_0$$ = 200 M$$^{-1}$$ and then [A]$$_0$$ = 0.005 M. The right way to make the exercise is to compare the inverse of concentration $$y$$ = 1/[A] at both moments $$x$$ = 0 s and at $$x$$ = 5.00 s, using the given equation, then: - At time $$x$$ = 0 s, $$y$$ = 1/[A] = 200 M$$^{-1}$$ and then [A]$$_0$$ = 0.005 M. - At time $$x$$ = 5.00 s, $$y$$ = 1/[A] = 200.148 M$$^{-1}$$ and then [A]$$_0$$ = 0.0049963 M. Then just a 0.074% of the reactant is consumed during the first 5.00 s. The mistake arises from ignoring that the consumed fraction of the reactant depends critically on the initial concentration (as does the half-life time), because the reaction has second order (not first order) kinetics. Thanks for the attention to this mistake.

Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Mistake in 7.2 Problem Examples Video: That 100 is wrong!
Input.posts:
In the 7.2 Problem Examples Video , there is a conceptual mistake at 2:13, when the lecturer introduces 100 as the 100% of the concentration (the initial concentration). However, what that assumption is actually telling us is that the initial concentration was 100 M!, which contradicts the given equation, which says that 1/[A]$$_0$$ = 200 M$$^{-1}$$ and then [A]$$_0$$ = 0.005 M. The right way to make the exercise is to compare the inverse of concentration $$y$$ = 1/[A] at both moments $$x$$ = 0 s and at $$x$$ = 5.00 s, using the given equation, then: - At time $$x$$ = 0 s, $$y$$ = 1/[A] = 200 M$$^{-1}$$ and then [A]$$_0$$ = 0.005 M. - At time $$x$$ = 5.00 s, $$y$$ = 1/[A] = 200.148 M$$^{-1}$$ and then [A]$$_0$$ = 0.0049963 M. Then just a 0.074% of the reactant is consumed during the first 5.00 s. The mistake arises from ignoring that the consumed fraction of the reactant depends critically on the initial concentration (as does the half-life time), because the reaction has second order (not first order) kinetics. Thanks for the attention to this mistake.

Input.threadtitle: Kinetics 1 - 2 do we also need to multiply the rate by a certain number?
Input.posts:
In the video e.g. 8:55, both sides have been multiplied by 5 to cancel the coefficient, but should we also multiply the 'Rate' by 5? Many thanks for your answers!
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Hey Xinyu, my name is Niranjana and I am a teaching assistant for this course. My apologies for the delay in responding to your question. Yes, you are correct that the rate related to BrO3- should also be multiplied by 5. It is important to remember that the rates you are dealing with are rates of change, not the overall rate of the reaction. These are two different things. In this question, in the Kinetics Activities Part 1 section in the 'Comparing Rate of Change for Reactants and Products' Lecture at 8:55 it is giving you the information for the rate of change of one reactant and asking you to use that information to figure out the rate of change of another reactant in the same reaction. More specifically, the rate of change for a reactant or product is the change in its concentration divided by the change in time (which is the same as the amount of time that the reaction has been occurring). So, given the rate of change for Br-, you have to divide that by 5 since there are five moles of Br- in the reaction and only 1 mole of BrO3- (which is the same as dividing its rate of change by 1 which you do not need to show since it does not the change the value of its rate of change). When you multiply the Br- side by 5, you must also multiply the BrO3- side by 5 so that you are doing the same thing to both sides of the equation, just like you would for an algebra problem. I hope this helps! Best, Niranjana

So, given the rate of change for Br-, you have to divide that by 5 since there are five moles of Br- in the reaction and only 1 mole of BrO3- (which is the same as dividing its rate of change by 1 which you do not need to show since it does not the change the value of its rate of change). When you multiply the Br- side by 5, you must also multiply the BrO3- side by 5 so that you are doing the same thing to both sides of the equation, just like you would for an algebra problem. I hope this helps! Best, Niranjana

Hey Valentin, my name is Niranjana and I am a teaching assistant for this course. You ask a very good question and Veneta was on the right track for this problem. The reason that the question asks the 'rate of change' is because you are only looking at the change in concentration of one reactant, not the overall reaction. If you had been asked to find the 'reaction rate', that is looking at the rate at which the products are formed in the overall reaction and not just one specific reactant or product. So yes, it is a general rule that the reaction rate should be positive because the reaction will \xA0continue to occur and products will be formed in the reaction. However, the 'rate of change' with respect to one specific reactant, in this case- the blue reactant, will be negative. As Veneta mentioned, the negative sign for the 'rate of change' is because the concentration of the reactant is decreasing as it is used up to make the product in the reaction. So you see a decrease in the concentration of the reactant and an increase in the rate of change for the product as it is being formed in the reaction. \xA0I hope this makes this question a little clearer for you! \xA0

If you had been asked to find the 'reaction rate', that is looking at the rate at which the products are formed in the overall reaction and not just one specific reactant or product. So yes, it is a general rule that the reaction rate should be positive because the reaction will \xA0continue to occur and products will be formed in the reaction. However, the 'rate of change' with respect to one specific reactant, in this case- the blue reactant, will be negative. As Veneta mentioned, the negative sign for the 'rate of change' is because the concentration of the reactant is decreasing as it is used up to make the product in the reaction. So you see a decrease in the concentration of the reactant and an increase in the rate of change for the product as it is being formed in the reaction. \xA0I hope this makes this question a little clearer for you! \xA0

A negative reaction means that the concentration of the reactant or the product is decreasing.\xA0 When you subtract the initial concentration from\xA0 the final concentration, you will get a negative number because the final concentration will be less than the initial concentration of the reactant or product and therefore the reaction rate is negative which is also the rate of change.\xA0 Since the reaction rate should always be positive, you must multiply the rate by a negative sign.

If you've ever taken physics or calc, distance is denoted by s. The velocity equation is v=Δs/Δt. Reaction rates are the same concept in chemistry, except instead of a change in distance, we want to find the change in the CONCENTRATION over time. Furthermore, if you know calculus, it will be easier for you to grasp/compute these concepts.

Jennifer and Valentin, I hope this helps:\xA0 The reaction rate or rate of change is the change in concentration of a reactant or a product with time.\xA0 The reactant usually decreases over time because it is being used to form the product.\xA0 The product usually increases over time because it is being formed.\xA0 The unit for the reaction rate is M/s.\xA0 This means molarity/second.\xA0 Molarity is moles/liter = tells the concentration of the reactant or product. The 's' stands for second = the time period between when the reaction started until it ended. The rate should always be positive. From what I can tell, the only time an answer involved a 'g' was when a chemical equation was written.\xA0 The subscript 'g' following a reactant or product represents the state of the substance. In this case, a 'g' indicates that the substance is a gas.\xA0 Did this help any?
